Representatives from across the political spectrum fear that this could lead to ridicule.
A Labour representative explained his group was concerned because “it rhymes with Twp and Pwp.”
For readers outside Wales: In Welsh, twp means “dustete”, and pwp means “beach”.
A representative for the Wales party Plaid Cymru said the group as a whole was “unsatisfied” and that they have suggested alternatives.
A representative for the Welsh section of the Conservative Party said his group was "open" to the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of the MWP is very close to the word "Muppet", which, in addition to being the name of some well-known dolls, is also a British slang word for "dust".
In this context, the Welsh letter W is pronounced in a similar way as the letter U is pronounced in the English Yorkshire dialect, more like a “uh” sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently drafting laws to introduce the name change, said: “Of course, it is the members themselves who have the final say as to what name they are to be referred to.”
The Government of Wales Act 2017 gave the Welsh National Assembly the authority to change its own name.
In June, the commission published the results of a public hearing that showed public support for renaming the National Assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
As for the title of the representatives, the Commission supported WMPs (Welsh Parliament Members), but the MWP option received the most support during the public hearing.
The representatives apparently suggest other options, but getting all parties to come to an agreement could lead to the head of parliamentary president Elin Jones, who is scheduled to deliver a draft legislation for the name change in the next few weeks.
The legislation surrounding the reform will include other changes to how the National Assembly functions, including rules for disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
The representatives have the last right to vote on what they will be called when debating the legislation.
