John Edward: Language skills are crucial for world citizens
Scotland’s free schools continue to exhibit academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another year of excellent exam results. These are underpinned by individual and joint success in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
These schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools, have more than 30,000 students across Scotland, and work hard to deliver the very best school experience to both students and parents.
Free schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
As an educational institution that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and in-demand elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, his words reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we see that language is at the top of the table with the highest percentages of attendance from free schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the examination grade A.
The data, obtained from the 74 member schools of the Free School Council, showed that 72 percent of students received the examination grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received A.
This illustrates that free schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a crucial skill children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as a subject choice is now valued at the same level as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for free schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 showed that, for the reasons employers cited for having difficulty holding a vacant position, 17 percent could be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become crucial in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter which career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey answered by more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language learning is now crucial for today’s children.
Knowing more languages, especially those related to emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland if each school teach in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages that are considered most valuable to the UK on the way to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a choice of languages to choose from at free schools, with teachers who are experts in this area.
Scottish schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that language is constantly crucial to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills”.
Free schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and distinction to Scotland’s youth.
It has to be done.
