North Korea 'in no way' to agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened mistrust of the United States and that the country would in no way agree to unilaterally release its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual general meeting that North Korea has carried out “significant benevolence measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We have not seen any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a gradual nuclear disarmament, where North Korea is rewarded for gradual disarmament steps, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done previously.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, where Kim promised to work against “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first release its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ and raises pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes ‘the declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream come true for people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader stressed in front of the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this disarmament case was South Korea, rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as stalled as it is.”
The tone of Ri’s speech, however, was very different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the mainland United States with North Korea’s missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
After threatening to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, Trump stood in front of the UN this year and praised Kim for being brave enough to take disarmament steps, but said much work still remains and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-armed.
