Students at Harvard take courses in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing culture of puking through the night with caffeine drinks as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best university often didn’t have a clue how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after giving a lecture on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why hasn’t anyone said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important it is with good sleep habits to be able to perform academically and athletically, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to start the course after they saw students suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a room in a dorm room, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risk of smoking,” Professor Czeisler said.
There is still some pride in being able to puke all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being an increasing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even as a means of weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, leading to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the classes to the professor last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before enrolling at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm for when to go to bed as well as for when to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep difficulties.
