Vaccine teaches immune system to recognize cancer cells as part of treatment
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient and changing them in a laboratory
The cells can now “see” a protein that is common in many cancers, and are then injected into the patient again.
A vaccine being tested has had promising results among patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, experienced ovarian cancer she suffered from disappear for over 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient, changing them in the lab so they can “see” a protein called HER2, which is typical of many cancers, and then injecting these cells back into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “The results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “drives the growth of various cancers,” including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer, and colorectal cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar method, in which immune cells were taken from the patient and "trained" to target cancer cells, has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
