It may contain contact lists, work lists, calendars, music libraries, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available on one browser at a time.
What is unique about the personal data storage online is that it is entirely up to the user who should have access to that type of information.
The company calls it “personal authorization through data.”
The idea behind Inrupt is, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, that the company will provide with the resources, process and relevant expertise to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers to work on the project, and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools found on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team don’t talk to Facebook and Google about whether or not they’re going to introduce something completely new, which will make their business models completely revamp overnight.
“We don’t ask for your permission.”
In a Medium post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s “mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Although he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about the next era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
