Germany's New Warship Delayed Again
The German Navy’s newest frigate was supposed to have been completed in 2014 to replace old warships from the days of the Cold War, but it won’t happen until early next year due to failing systems and galloping costs, local media reported.
The completion of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the brand-new frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted a military spokesperson.
The vessel was supposed to have been handed over to the Navy in 2014, but the major post-delivery problems pursued the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class navy ordered all the way back in 2007, will replace the old frigates of the Bremen-class.
It has been agreed that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to use the latest frigates for up to two years away from home port.
However, ongoing delays mean that the advanced warships – which were said to give Germany strength at sea – will already be outdated before they are put into service.
The fateful F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media mentioned a number of important "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software defects were particularly important since Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels were to be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors – only half the crew of older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also revealed that the ship has an enormous excess weight, which reduces performance and limits the Navy’s ability to make upgrades in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is estimated to be twice as heavy as similar ships of the same class that were used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the price tag on the entire project – including crew training – has also started to become a problem.
It is claimed to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros – from the original 2.2 billion euros.
The problems surrounding the new frigates are particularly significant in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German government’s defence committee, confirmed that the navy actually “goes empty for usable ships.”
The official said the problem has escalated over time because old ships were out of service, but no new vessels arrived.
He regrets that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could be used by the Navy.
The National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out at a land estate in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the landscape in the pursuit of food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats, as well as brownlings and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Experts' sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and which species do what.
Then, a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures should be introduced, for example, to plant grazing land and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects breeding grounds and habitat restriction.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with flypaper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house taxes.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, mapping of breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland’s first and only own bat reserve at the Threeve land estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threeave we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping the bats before carrying out maintenance on a property since the inadvertent destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps devastate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species, we simply don’t know how the populations are doing.”
