Speaking at the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to progress in combating terrorism,” he said.
The state continues to rebuild the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
All conditions are now arranged for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
In addition, there are six million people still living in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome help to rebuild the destroyed country.
But he stressed that conditional aid or aid from countries that supported the rebellion would not be accepted.
