Algae bloom update: Concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotty blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are detected around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red algae has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported at or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, high to low concentrations in Charlotte County, and low to high concentrations in Charlotte County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There were no reports of irritation in the airways northwest of Florida during the past week.
